<br>
Ibudin 57th Necromancer of Immortal Mercy <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/usoledorin.showPublicProfile?language=EN>soledorin</A> at: 1/10/02 5:51:39 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#383838><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/uclanmcstump.showPublicProfile?language=EN>ClanMcStump</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Elite Poster</span><br> <font color=#ff0000>(1/10/02 5:53:01 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=805.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Planes and Guns</span><hr size=1> I can think of a couple problems with arming the crew.<br>
<br>
   1)  Any armed crew member could be disarmed by a potential hijacker who could then use the firearm against other crewmembers or passangers.<br>
<br>
   2)  Firefights at 10,000+ feet are very very bad.  Bullets can fairly easily penetrate the hull of most commercial airliners.  A hole the size of a quarter in the hull of a plane flying at 12,000 feet would quickly become a much larger hole as the cabin decompresses.  This could result in passengers and crew being sucked out of the plane.  This would also result in a tremendous (not to mention extremely rapid) loss of altitude.<br>
<br>
   3)  Firefights at 10,000+ feet are very very bad.  Picture armed crew and armed hijackers firing at each other across a cabin full of unarmed passnegers.<br>
<br>
   4)  Costs.  Imagine trying to buy handguns for every member of a single airline company.  And then having to pay to have those crewmembers trained in the use of firearms.  Then think of what said airlines insurance rates would be like.<br>
<br>
And those reasons are just the ones I can think of without putting any real amount of thought into the subject.<br>
<br>
Stymp McStump, Godling of Casus Belli<br>
