<img src=http://24.116.149.140/tux.jpg height=120 width=120></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#383838><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/bayonaero.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=brynie5287>Brynie5287</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>New to the block</span><br> <font color=#ff0000>(1/10/02 9:28:11 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=805.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Planes and Guns</span><hr size=1> Interesting thread. Couple of points of information on arming crews and possibly passengers on<br>
commercial flights<br>
<br>
1. Puncturing the skin of the aircraft. A few aeronautical engineers have taken a look at this over the<br>
    years for the military. Planes can be punctured many times and not lose discernable  integrity.<br>
<br>
    Sky Marshals are equipped with special Fragable ammo. It penetrates human skin but not the<br>
    skin of aircraft. This type of ammunition would also decrease the potential of collateral damage<br>
    during a firefight. It would be simple to equip flight crews with the same ammunition.<br>
<br>
2. Training. Most flight crews are ex-military and so have basic small arms training. Since Sept 11, 2001<br>
    several private Firearm Training companies have offered FREE training to any pilot who wants it.<br>
    Front Site being just one of these companies.<br>
<br>
3. Accidental discharge. Based on NSC, CDC and Insurance Industry data, the chance for a person trained in<br>
   Firearms to accidentally discharge a weapon is extremely small (you are more likely to be injured by <br>
   suffocation during swallowing [National Safety Councils &quot;1997 Accident Fact Book&quot; which is the most recent<br>
   year available to me]. Add the fragable ammo to the equation and it becomes a non-issue.<br>
<br>
4. Hijacker disarming crew member. Of the 2.5 million defensive gun uses every year, the percentage of<br>
    criminals who disarm the victim is less then 3%. Consider that you are far more likely to survive<br>
    a violent encounter if you are armed. In cases where there was injury to a robbery victim, injury to<br>
    the victim occurred in the following percentages: victim resisting with a gun 6%, victim did nothing <br>
    at all 25%, victim resisted with a knife 40%, victim took a non-violent stance 45%. <br>
<br>
5. Costs to arm pilots and flight crews. Most flight crews are ex-military. Most ex-military I know have<br>
   personal firearms. Costs would depend on whether standardization was required for arming the crew or if<br>
   they would be allowed to use personal sidearms. Even if the airline or government required standardization,<br>
   a decent semi-automatic can be purchased for $650 (Think Glock 30 here). Add costs for practice<br>
   (say 5,000 rounds a year and bi-weekly trips to the range) and you have a flight crewperson equipped<br>
   initially for less then $3,000 the first year and $2,000 for each year after. This assumes standard retail<br>
   prices which I am certain would be less for a mass purchase.<br>
   If groups decided to reload, you can drop the practice costs by half. <br>
   <br>
   I have no idea what insurance rates would be. However, I doubt they would be prohibitive as EL AL<br>
   commercial pilots/crew have been armed for years. Anyone remember the last time an EL AL flight was<br>
   hijacked?<br>
<br>
Some of the info comes from:<br>
<br>
   &quot;More Guns, Less Crime&quot; by Prof John Lott<br>
<br>
   &quot;Seven Myths of Gun Control&quot; by Richard Poe<br>
<br>
Before anyone just says &quot;Brynie= NUT&quot; let me relate a personal experience. When I first moved into<br>
my current home, I has robbed twice while I was at home in bed. In the second case, I called the local<br>
sheriffs while the robber was still present. The sheriffs took 20 min to respond. Thankfully the robber stayed to the living room for 5 min before departing with some serious electronics.t. <br>
<br>
Because of this I decided to research obtaining a firearm (forget alarms as it was obvious the police were<br>
not going to go come any faster). I read for 6 months, crunched numbers from various studies and<br>
had my father (ex professor of statistics &amp; research methodology and a LONG TIME GUN HATER) review<br>
the same studies. We independently came to the same conclusion, that the research about gun ownership<br>
decreasing and deterring crime was accurate and compelling.<br>
<br>
Good Cheer,<br>
Brynie<br>
